Items.Title: Member of County Assembly
Items.Description: Duties, Responsibilities, Qualifications
Items.Content1:
1. The National Assembly represents the people of the constituencies and special interests in the National Assembly.

2.The National Assembly deliberates on and resolves issues of concern to the people.

3. The National Assembly enacts legislation in accordance with Part 4 of this Chapter.

4. The National Assembly: 
(a) determines the allocation of national revenue between the levels of government, as provided in Part 4 of Chapter Twelve;
(b) appropriates funds for expenditure by the national government and other national State organs; 
(c) exercises oversight over national revenue and its expediture.

5. The National Assembly:
(a) reviews the conduct in office of the President, the Deputy President and other State officers and initiates the process of removing them from office 
(b) exercises oversight of State organs.

6. The National Assembly approves declarations of war and extensions of states of emergency.

Items.Title: County Governor
Items.Description: Duties, Responsibilities, Qualifications
Items.Content1:
1. Diligently execute the functions and exercise the authority provided for in the Constitution and legislation. 
2. Perform such State functions within the county as the President may from time to time assign on the basis of mutual consultations.
3. Represent the county in national and international fora and events.
4. Appoint, with the approval of the county assembly, the county executive committee.
5. Constitute the county executive committee portfolio structure to respond to the functions and competencies assigned to and transferred to each county.
6. Submitubmit the county plans and policies to the county assembly for approval.
7. Consider, approve and assent to bills passed by the county assembly.
8. Chair meetings of the county executive committee.

Items.Title: County Senator
Items.Description: Duties, Responsibilities, Qualifications
Items.Content1:
1. The Senate represents the counties, and serves to protectthe interests of the counties and their governments.
2. The Senate participates in the law-making function of Parliament by considering, debating and approving Bills concerning counties, as provided in Articles 109 to 113.
3. The Senate determines the allocation of national revenue among counties, as provided in Article 217, and exercises oversight  over national revenue allocated to the county governments.
4. The Senate participates in the oversight of State officers by considering and determining any resolution to remove the Presiden or Deputy President from office in accordance with Article 145.

Items.Title: Member of Parliament
Items.Description: Duties, Responsibilities, Qualifications
Items.Content2:
1. The Member of Parliament represents the people of the constituencies and special interests in the Parliament.
2. The Member of Parliament deliberates on and resolves issues of concern to the people.
3. The Member of Parliament enacts legislation in accordance with Part 4 of this Chapter.
4. The Member of Parliament: 
(a) determines the allocation of national revenue between the levels of government, as provided in Part 4 of Chapter Twelve;
(b) appropriates funds for expenditure by the national government and other national State organs; 
(c) exercises oversight over national revenue and its expediture.

5. The Member of Parliament:
(a) reviews the conduct in office of the President, the Deputy President and other State officers and initiates the process of removing them from office 
(b) exercises oversight of State organs.

Items.Title: County Women Rep
Items.Description: Duties, Responsibilities, Qualifications
Items.Content2:
1. Balancing the gender equation in parliament by creating room for more women in parliament (affirmative action)
2. Primarily promote the interests of women and the girl child within their counties (and by large, nationwide) by coming up with legislation that favors and suits the women and girls within their dominions.
3. Through legislation, they should lobby and advocate for the rights, freedoms and interests of the women and girls, who are perceived by the society to be the 'weaker sex' in order to uplift them to the standard where they are considered at par with their male counterparts.
4. Formulate legislative policies that uplift the social, economic, and political status of women and girls in the country. Nevertheless, this advocacy does not necessarily involve advocating for immediate needs for the women and girls, such as sanitary towels and boreholes.
5. Addressing the challenges that face the women and girls in this country due to persistent marginalization and neglect by the patriarchal society. This includes ensuring, through legislation and policy formulation, that majority of the female population has a certain level of affordable access to basic needs and wants, rights and freedoms, privileges and protections.

Items.Title: Why vote
Items.Description: Why you need to vote
Items.Content2:
1. Voting provides an opportunity to choose a leader of your choice
2. Voting provides an opportunity to vie in elections. By law, only registered voters are allowed to vie for elections.
3. You safeguard your rights and freedoms as provided for in the constitution
4. You give legitimacy to leaders. By electing their leaders, voters givetheir consent to be led by whoever they have chosen and to reject those who fail to sufficiently represent their interests.

Items.Title: Voter Rights
Items.Description: Your voting rights as the citizen of Kenya
Items.Content2:
1. Every citizen is free to make political choices,which includes the right
	(a) to form, or participate in forming, a political party
	(b) to participate in the activities of, or recruit members for,a political party
	(c) to campaign for a political party or cause
2. Every citizen has the right to free, fair and regular elections based on universal suffrage and the free expression of the will of the electors for
	(a) any elective public body or office established under this Constitution
	(b) any office of any political party of which the citizen is a member
3. Every adult citizen has the right, without unreasonable restrictions
	(a) to be registered as a voter
	(b) to vote by secret ballot in any election or referendum
	(c) to be a candidate for public office, or office within a political party of which the citizen is a member and, if elected, to hold office
